data.message:
sysdef support for empty partition

the following scheme applied for empty partitions:
`<partition/>` result to n=0,str=NULL;
`<partition>(<name/>|<name><element/></>)</>` result to n=1,str="";

Add mid table also for non-mutable inside mutable

For this:

    struct S {
        @optional bool a;
    };

    @mutable
    struct T {
        S b;
    };

the member id table is required for field "a" even though T is mutable.  Instead of
short-circuiting on encountering a mutable struct, process the fields while accounting for
them being used as members of a mutable struct.

Signed-off-by: Erik Boasson <eb@ilities.com>

Additional fix for KEY flags in opcodes for nested collections

Fixes a bug in IDLC that caused incorrect opcode generation for data
types where a nested struct is used both as a non-key and a key member
in the top-level type. The issue was in the `get_ctype_keys` function,
which was not recursing into the element type of nested collections.

An example of a data type affected by this issue:

struct n2 { short a; };
struct n1 { sequence<n2> b[2]; };
struct t { n1 c; @key n1 d; };

Signed-off-by: Dennis Potman <dennis@zettascale.tech>

ddsi_time_t.seconds should be uint32_t

ref DDSI-RTPS 9.3.2.1 IDL Definitions
struct Time_t {
  unsigned long seconds; // time in seconds
  unsigned long fraction; // time in sec/2^32
};

Signed-off-by: binbowang <binbowang1987@163.com>

Type builder: keys from non-mutable base types

This fixes a null pointer dereference in comparing key ids in dynamically constructing
a (de)serializer when the key is an inherited composite key in a non-mutable type, e.g.:

    @final struct K { long a; };
    @final struct Base { @key K a; };
    @final struct Derived : Base { };

Signed-off-by: Erik Boasson <eb@ilities.com>

Skip optionals completely when deserializing a key (#2040)

* Skip optionals completely when deserializing a key

The serialized key only contains the key fields and when deserializing a key one must skip
everything else.  The deserialization (and printing) code incorrectly read the boolean
indicating presence of an optional field in cases like:

    struct S {
      @optional long x;
      @key long y;
    };

This commit fixes it by first checking whether a key is being deserialized, skipping the
checks for the presence of an optional field if it is.  (Note that optional fields can not
be key fields.)

Signed-off-by: Erik Boasson <eb@ilities.com>

* Overlooked the "normalize" case

Signed-off-by: Erik Boasson <eb@ilities.com>

---------

Signed-off-by: Erik Boasson <eb@ilities.com>

Do not change type in typelib making key holder

Type assignability for structs can require constructing a key holder type, which in turn
involves marking all fields as key fields for a struct that has no key fields defined,
e.g., when:

    struct Inner {
      long a, b;
    };
    struct Outer {
      @key Inner k;
    };

the key holder type will constructing a type where "a" and "b" are annotated as keys.  The
code for doing this incorrectly modified the input type already in the library, rather
than setting the flag on the new key holder type.

Obviously, silently changing the type in the library is bad.  It was observed because the
change affects the type identifier (without changing where the type is in the index) and
the mismatch got flagged while processing a type lookup reply.

Signed-off-by: Erik Boasson <eb@ilities.com>

Fix ENABLE_IPV6/ENABLE_SOURCE_SPECIFIC_MULTICAST

This fixes these two CMake options in the sense that:

* It now does AUTO/ON/OFF, with ON requiring the platform to support it, OFF not caring in
  the slightest and AUTO enabling it only if the platform supports it;

* It now does both entirely in the ddsrt CMakeLists.txt and puts the result in
  ddsrt/config.h;

* There is no more a DDS_HAS_SSM flag in dds/features.h;

* There are no more defines of DDSRT_HAVE_SSM in ddsrt/sockets/{posix,windows}.h (that
  were never used in the past);

* All code uses the same definitions.

The CMake bits seem to work fine on the CI platforms.

Signed-off-by: Erik Boasson <eb@ilities.com>

Speed up attribute handling with fancy quotes

This

   if (n == 0xe2 && (peek_chars (st, "\xe2\x80\x9c", 0) || peek_chars (st, "\xe2\x80\x98", 0))) {
     /* allow fancy unicode quotes (U+201c .. U+201d and U+2018 ... U+2019) in
        UTF-8 representation because email clients like to rewrite plain ones,
        and this has caused people trouble several times already */
     (void) next_char (st); (void) next_char (st);
     const unsigned char c = (unsigned char) next_char (st);
     const unsigned char endm[4] = { 0xe2, 0x80, (unsigned char) (c + 1), 0 };
     tok = next_token_string (st, payload, (const char *) endm);
   }

nice little hack caused so many calls to strlen en memcmp that it timed
out on OSS-Fuzz.  It doesn't seem like an issue for actual
configurations and it does terminate in a few seconds on a normal
machine, but OSS-Fuzz also matters.  Fortunately, this case can be fixed
rather easily.

Signed-off-by: Erik Boasson <eb@ilities.com>

Initialize some additional fields in rtps_init

This helps with tests that just need a "gv" pointer, because this way:

  struct ddsi_domaingv gv;
  thread_states_init ();
  ddsi_config_init_default (&gv.config);
  rtps_config_prep (&gv, NULL);
  rtps_init (&gv);

is sufficient and compatible with the obvious clean up code.

Signed-off-by: Erik Boasson <eb@ilities.com>

Changed NetworkInterface ip member to address

//CycloneDDS/Domain/General/Interfaces/NetworkInterface

Attributes: address

Fix idlc typedef for scoped name

This fixes a bug in IDLC that causes the compilation to fail when
the IDL contains a typedef with a scoped name as type definition, e.g.

module m1 {
  struct s1 { long a; };
};
typedef m1::s1 m2;

Signed-off-by: Dennis Potman <dennis@zettascale.tech>

Typebuilder fix for union-members with multiple case labels

This fixes a bug in the topic descriptor generation that caused an incorrect
opcode at index 0 when the type has a union that has multiple labels for a
member with a member-type that is represented in-union (after the union cases)
in the generated ops, e.g.:

  struct t { long t1; };
  union u switch(octet) {
    case 1: case 2:
      sequence<t> u1;
  };

Signed-off-by: Dennis Potman <dennis@zettascale.tech>

Add warnings for when parsing unsupported annotations

The following annotations are part of the XTypes/IDLV4.0 spec, but
their parsing is not yet implemented:
@verbatim
@service
@oneway
@ami
@ignore_literal_names
@non_serialized
When they are encountered, a warning is given to the user, which can
be suppressed using the command line option "no-unsupported-annotations"

Signed-off-by: Martijn Reicher <martijn.reicher@zettascale.tech>

Consistency of type consistency QoS serialization

This brings the serialization of the type consistency QoS in line with
the deserialization of it, which, I believe is consistent with the
XTypes 1.3 spec:

  @extensibility(APPENDABLE) @nested
  struct TypeConsistencyEnforcementQosPolicy {
    TypeConsistencyKind kind;
    boolean ignore_sequence_bounds;
    boolean ignore_string_bounds;
    boolean ignore_member_names;
    boolean prevent_type_widening;
    boolean force_type_validation;
  };

Signed-off-by: Erik Boasson <eb@ilities.com>

Add hash add/remove that check for success

Most of the time when ddsrt_hh_add or ddsrt_hh_remove is called, these
are expected to succeed because the key was absent at the time of the
call to "add", or present at the time of the call to "remove".
Asserting this leads to a common stanza:

    const int x = ddsrt_hh_add (...);
    assert (x);
    (void) x;

It seems sensible to provide wrappers that do this automatically.

Signed-off-by: Erik Boasson <eb@ilities.com>

to_ser_ref must increment serdata refcount

The serdata is needed later on for invoking to_ser_unref.  Not
incrementing the refcount can result in a use-after-free, for example
when a sample included in a queued retransmit packet is dropped from the
WHC before the payload references in the queued packet are released
after sending it.

